input.prompt:
Implement the "auto-generated session title" feature that surfaces AI-generated session titles from Claude Code and Codex SDKs into the workspace sidebar.

## Context

The Claude Agent SDK auto-generates session summaries/titles after the first turn. The Codex SDK emits `thread/name/updated` events. Currently, our app doesn't capture either of these. The sidebar shows workspace titles from `getWorkspaceDisplayName()` which already prioritizes `workspace.title` over the celestial slug — so we just need to feed the title data through.

The database columns `sessions.title` and `workspaces.title` already exist but are unused for auto-generated titles.

## Implementation Plan (6 files, ~60 lines)

### 1. `shared/agent-events.ts` — Add new canonical event

Add to `AGENT_EVENT_NAMES`:
```typescript
SESSION_TITLE: "session.title",
```

Add a new Zod schema and type:
```typescript
export const SessionTitleEventSchema = z.object({
  type: z.literal("session.title"),
  sessionId: z.string(),
  agentType: AgentTypeSchema,
  title: z.string(),
});
export type SessionTitleEvent = z.infer<typeof SessionTitleEventSchema>;
```

Add `SessionTitleEvent` to the `AgentEvent` discriminated union and `AgentEventSchema`.

### 2. `apps/sidecar/event-broadcaster.ts` — Add emitter method

Add a new static method:
```typescript
static emitSessionTitle(sessionId: string, agentType: string, title: string): void {
  EventBroadcaster.emitEvent({
    type: "session.title",
    sessionId,
    agentType,
    title,
  } as AgentEvent);
}
```

### 3. `apps/sidecar/agents/claude/message-processor.ts` — Emit after first turn

When `cleanMessage.type === "result" && cleanMessage.subtype === "success"` (around line 197), after the existing session.idle emission, call `listSessions()` from the Claude Agent SDK to get the auto-generated summary:

```typescript
// After session.idle emission (line ~205), add title fetching:
if (!ctx.titleEmitted) {
  ctx.titleEmitted = true;
  // Fire-and-forget — title is best-effort, don't block the stream
  void (async () => {
    try {
      const { listSessions } = await import("@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk");
      const sessions = await listSessions({ dir: session.cwd });
      // Find our session by agent_session_id captured earlier
      const agentSessionId = /* need to get this */ undefined;
      // Actually, cleanMessage has session_id field
      const sdkSessionId = String(cleanMessage.session_id || "");
      const match = sessions.find(s => s.sessionId === sdkSessionId);
      if (match?.summary) {
        EventBroadcaster.emitSessionTitle(opts.sessionId, "claude", match.summary);
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(`[${opts.generatorId}] Failed to fetch session title:`, error);
    }
  })();
}
```

IMPORTANT: For the `listSessions` call, you need to figure out exactly what the Claude Agent SDK exports. Check `node_modules/@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk/sdk.d.ts` for the `listSessions` function signature. It takes `{ dir?: string }` and returns `Promise<SDKSessionInfo[]>`. The `SDKSessionInfo` has `sessionId` and `summary` fields.

Also add `titleEmitted: boolean` to the `StreamContext` type in `apps/sidecar/agents/claude/stream-context.ts`.

IMPORTANT: The `session_id` from SDK messages is the Claude Code internal session ID. It's already captured in `message-processor.ts` around line 94-95 (`cleanMessage.session_id`). You need to use this to match against the `listSessions()` output.

### 4. `apps/sidecar/agents/codex/codex-handler.ts` — Handle thread name event

In the Codex handler's event processing loop (where it iterates `for await (const event of events)`), add handling for the `thread/name/updated` event:

```typescript
// When processing Codex events:
if (event.method === "thread/name/updated") {
  const name = event.params?.thread?.name || event.params?.name;
  if (name) {
    EventBroadcaster.emitSessionTitle(sessionId, "codex", name);
  }
  continue; // or just don't skip other processing
}
```

Read the codex-handler.ts file first to understand the exact event processing pattern, then add the title handling in the right place.

### 5. `apps/backend/src/services/agent/event-handler.ts` — Dispatch new event

Add a new match arm before `.exhaustive()`:

```typescript
.with({ type: "session.title" }, (e) => {
  console.log(`[AgentEvent] session.title: session=${e.sessionId} title="${e.title}"`);
  persistAndInvalidate(persistSessionTitle(e), SESSION_RESOURCES, e.sessionId);
})
```

Also import `persistSessionTitle` from `./persistence`.

### 6. `apps/backend/src/services/agent/persistence.ts` — DB write

Add the persistence function:

```typescript
/** Update session title and auto-set workspace title if not already set. */
export function persistSessionTitle(event: SessionTitleEvent): WriteResult<void> {
  const db = getDatabase();
  try {
    db.transaction(() => {
      // Always update session title
      db.prepare("UPDATE sessions SET title = ?, updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = ?")
        .run(event.title, event.sessionId);
      // Auto-set workspace title only if not already set (preserves PR titles and user renames)
      db.prepare(
        `UPDATE workspaces SET title = ?
         WHERE id = (SELECT workspace_id FROM sessions WHERE id = ?)
         AND title IS NULL`
      ).run(event.title, event.sessionId);
    })();
    return { ok: true, value: undefined };
  } catch (error) {
    const msg = getErrorMessage(error);
    console.error(`[AgentPersistence] Failed to persist session.title:`, msg);
    return { ok: false, error: msg };
  }
}
```

Import the `SessionTitleEvent` type from `@shared/agent-events`.

## Important Notes

- Read each file before editing to understand the exact patterns and imports
- Follow existing code patterns exactly (ts-pattern matching, WriteResult, getErrorMessage, etc.)
- The `listSessions` import from claude-agent-sdk should use the same import style as `query` in claude-handler.ts
- For stream-context.ts, look at how it's structured and add `titleEmitted` with a default of `false`
- The Codex event structure may vary — read the codex-handler.ts to understand the exact event shape
- No frontend changes needed — the sidebar already displays workspace.title when set
- No schema changes needed — both title columns already exist

