Perfect. Now I have all the information needed. Let me provide you with a comprehensive review of the "session title" feature implementation.

## Session Title Feature Implementation Review

The changes implement automatic session title generation from Claude Agent SDK summaries. Here's the complete picture:

### 1. **shared/agent-events.ts** (Lines 378-384)
Added canonical event type for session titles:
```typescript
export const SessionTitleEventSchema = z.object({
  type: z.literal("session.title"),
  sessionId: z.string(),
  agentType: AgentTypeSchema,
  title: z.string(),
});
```

**Status:** Well-scoped, clean addition to the discriminated union.

### 2. **apps/sidecar/event-broadcaster.ts** (Lines 285-292)
Added typed emission method:
```typescript
emitSessionTitle(sessionId: string, agentType: AgentType, title: string): void {
  this.emitEvent({
    type: AGENT_EVENT_NAMES.SESSION_TITLE,
    sessionId,
    agentType,
    title,
  });
}
```

**Status:** Minimal, follows existing emit patterns. No issues.

### 3. **apps/sidecar/agents/claude/stream-context.ts** (Lines 15-32)
Added `titleEmitted` flag to StreamContext:
```typescript
export interface StreamContext {
  // ... existing fields ...
  titleEmitted: boolean;
}
```

**Status:** Clean separation of concerns. Single responsibility.

### 4. **apps/sidecar/agents/claude/message-processor.ts** (Lines 208-233)
The **most complex and interesting part** — implemented title fetching:

```typescript
// Best-effort title fetch: after the first successful turn, ask the SDK
// for its auto-generated session summary and emit it as a canonical event.
// Fire-and-forget — title is cosmetic, don't block the stream.
if (!ctx.titleEmitted && session.cwd) {
  ctx.titleEmitted = true;
  const sdkSessionId = cleanMessage.session_id ? String(cleanMessage.session_id) : null;

  void (async () => {
    try {
      const { listSessions } = await import("@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk");
      const sessions = await listSessions({ dir: session.cwd, limit: 20 });
      const matched = sdkSessionId
        ? sessions.find((s) => s.sessionId === sdkSessionId)
        : null;
      const title = matched?.summary;
      if (title) {
        EventBroadcaster.emitSessionTitle(opts.sessionId, "claude", title);
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(`[${opts.generatorId}] Failed to fetch session title:`, getErrorMessage(error));
    }
  })();
}
```

**Status:** Good architectural decision — fire-and-forget async. However, there's a **simplification opportunity** (see below).

### 5. **apps/backend/src/services/agent/event-handler.ts** (Lines 143-148)
Dispatch handler:
```typescript
.with({ type: "session.title" }, (e) => {
  console.log(`[AgentEvent] session.title: session=${e.sessionId} title="${e.title}"`);
  persistAndInvalidate(persistSessionTitle(e), SESSION_RESOURCES, e.sessionId);
})
```

**Status:** Clean, follows established pattern with `persistAndInvalidate()`.

### 6. **apps/backend/src/services/agent/persistence.ts** (Lines 250-274)
Database write with auto-set workspace title:

```typescript
export function persistSessionTitle(event: SessionTitleEvent): WriteResult<void> {
  const db = getDatabase();
  try {
    db.transaction(() => {
      // Always update session title
      db.prepare(
        `UPDATE sessions SET title = ?, updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = ?`
      ).run(event.title, event.sessionId);

      // Auto-set workspace title only if not already set (preserves PR titles and user renames)
      db.prepare(
        `UPDATE workspaces SET title = ?
         WHERE id = (SELECT workspace_id FROM sessions WHERE id = ?)
         AND title IS NULL`
      ).run(event.title, event.sessionId);
    })();
    return { ok: true, value: undefined };
  } catch (error) {
    // ...
  }
}
```

**Status:** Excellent UX design — auto-sets workspace title only if null. Clean transaction boundaries.

### Test Coverage
- **stream-context.test.ts** — Minimal but sufficient (tests initialization)
- **message-processor.test.ts** — 100+ lines, good coverage for title emit logic
- **agent-event-handler.test.ts** — Clean mock setup, tests persistence + invalidation flow

---

## Simplification Opportunities

### 1. **Hardcoded "claude" agent type in message-processor.ts (Line 116)**
```typescript
EventBroadcaster.emitAssistantMessage(
  opts.sessionId,
  "claude",  // ← Hardcoded
  { ... },
  opts.model
);
```

**Opportunity:** Pass `agentType` in `ProcessMessageOptions` instead of hardcoding. Makes code provider-agnostic and testable for future Codex integration.

**Impact:** Small refactor, ~3 locations affected (lines 116, 135, 169, 200, 205, 224, 239).

### 2. **Dynamic import in message-processor.ts (Line 217)**
```typescript
const { listSessions } = await import("@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk");
```

**Observations:**
- Good: Lazy-loads SDK only when needed (fire-and-forget context)
- Concern: This is the ONLY place importing the SDK after message processing. If the SDK is already imported elsewhere (session init), the dynamic import is redundant.

**Suggestion:** Check if `listSessions` is already available in `SessionState` or via a pre-imported module. If not, keep as-is (lazy loading is actually a good optimization for cosmetic features).

### 3. **Missing null safety in title emission (Line 223)**
```typescript
const title = matched?.summary;
if (title) {  // ← Good check, but title type is `string | undefined`
  EventBroadcaster.emitSessionTitle(opts.sessionId, "claude", title);
}
```

**Current:** Already safe (conditional check prevents emission of falsy titles). ✅

---

## Summary

**Overall Quality:** 8/10 — Well-structured, fire-and-forget pattern is solid, DB transaction is correct.

**Key Strengths:**
- ✅ Non-blocking, cosmetic feature won't slow down message streaming
- ✅ Graceful error handling (silent failure, logged)
- ✅ Smart DB logic: auto-sets workspace title only if null
- ✅ Clear canonical event design
- ✅ Good test coverage for a new feature

**Low-Hanging Refactoring:**
1. Extract `agentType` to `ProcessMessageOptions` (3-4 line change, better code reuse)
2. Verify SDK import strategy is optimal (check if `listSessions` could be imported at module level)

The implementation is **production-ready** — the simplification opportunities are nice-to-have improvements, not blockers.

